metadata.name: FXHASH Generative Logo #378
metadata.description:
Unique iteration of the first Generative Token minted on fxhash.

It also servers as the actual logo of the platform. It represents the generative processes driving fxhash tokens. Generative Tokens are fed with a unique hash to produce unique outputs based on the hash ‚Äî they are functions with a hash as single input.

The growth that comes out of the text is driven by a "Dividing-Aggregating Walkers" (DAW) algorithm. The hash drives all the DAW settings, as well as a mutation factor which is responsible for changes in each Walker parameters as they divide.

Some iterations will produce very simple outputs whereas others might be more chaotic.

Piece by @ciphrd for fxhash

metadata.name: Tumble Down Light Factory #405
metadata.description:
Tumble Down Light Factory is an interpretation of light installations & murals.

It attempts to trigger the feeling of coming up on a new block in a new city to discover an unexpected piece of art that is stories tall or entering a new room, knowing there will be a projection dominating the space with its light and color.

This is an abstract distillation of those things and those feelings.

Each composition is initially drawn to a hidden ‚Äútemplate‚Äù canvas which is sampled and then rendered on the main canvas in various ways after applying some transforms to give it some depth (and so you can actually see it.)

Viewing in full-screen is nice. You should try it.

T : Save hidden ‚Äòtemplate‚Äô image
S : Save current resolution
1 -> 5 : Save low -> high resolution

metadata.name: Rain Ritual #16
metadata.description:
Every windy gust.... every breeze, gave the restless grasses a chance to spread their suggestive rumours, their spurious gossip. All the while, Old Ones of the field towered above, chanting to their wrathful Sky God for more rain.... Always more rain. 

Instructions 
Intended for high resolutions. Use the following keys once render is complete, to export (letters export without a border) 

Square mode 
   1 (q) : 2048x2048  
   2 (w) : 3072x3072 
   3 (e) : 4096x4096 
   4 (r) : 5120x5120 

Landscape mode (increases spacing between objects to preserve aspect ratio) 
   5 (t) : 2560x1440 
   6 (y) : 3840x2160 
   7 (u) : 5128x2880 
   8 (I) : 7680x4320 

Note: Generated textures are resolution dependant, resulting in very slight differences across resolutions. Composition however, remains identical. 

Browsers 
Tested with Chrome, Edge and Firefox on Windows, Chrome on Mac. 
Note for Firefox users : Ensure "Use hardware acceleration" is ticked ‚Äì Found in Settings / Performance. Other advanced settings to enable include : gfx.canvas.accelerated,  gfx.direct2d.force-enabled and gfx.offscreencanvas.enabled - Unfortunately even with these, Firefox appears slower than other browsers.  

Shoulders of Giants [license text and links included in source]

- JS Topology Suite "JSTS", a port of Java Topology Suite "JTS" - High-level Geometry library 

Additional JS functions

metadata.name: Pobbles #88
metadata.description:
The pobbles are generative blob-rocks: staring in silence, sometimes half-smiling, generally bored. 

‚Ä¢ The pobbles are digital recreations of a series of rock-doodles by S.F.Kislev (my big brother). They are an attempt to capture a specific, singular handwriting, and evolve it using code. 
‚Ä¢ See the original, 2014 handmade version here - https://pobbles.tez.page..
‚Ä¢ Alternative titles considered include Peggles‚Ñ¢, Plops‚Ñ¢, Blobbies‚Ñ¢, Floofs‚Ñ¢, Flintstones‚Ñ¢, Lardies‚Ñ¢, Plumps‚Ñ¢, Fats‚Ñ¢ and Wet-Ones‚Ñ¢. 
‚Ä¢ The pobbles are written entirely in paper.js and p5.js. 
‚Ä¢ The pobbles are an effort to take generative art into the realm of the cute. 
‚Ä¢ They work well with toddlers.

metadata.name: SoulFish #173
metadata.description:
Named after the artist Wu Che-Yu, the soul fish was born in the void and crystallized from human emotions.

Fluttering silently and slowly, their bodies almost disappeared in the light of the deep sea.
The fish swims freely, and this is the happiness of the fish.
If we are not a fish, how do we know the joy of a fish?
How do we know that we do not know the joy of fish?
We will only learn about it when we come to the riverside.

Inspired by ZhuƒÅngz«ê: "The Debate on the Joy of Fish" c. 3rd century BC

Interactivities:
> Key S: Save
> Holding mouse in different directions: Swim 
> Click and let the fish touch the Bubbles

metadata.name: PWTC #83
metadata.description:
PWTC (Play with tubes and circles) is an artistic exercise of creation by repetition. Composed with only 2 simple shapes and a limited color palette, the beauty of the patterns generated comes from the repetition and random ordering made possible by the junction of artistic thought in intersection with code.

#Main Features

* ORIENTATION ‚Äì 60% horizontal; 40% vertical
* TEXTURE ‚Äì 50% point; 30% scribble; 20% scratch
* GREY SCALE ‚Äì 5% chance
* INVERT ‚Äì 2,5% chance

#Royalties split: 20% for minters.

* Minters in the first stage of DA will receive a printed version *

June 30, 2022

Generative Token by Eder Cruz + Morbeck for fxhash.

metadata.name: Tree Skyness #228
metadata.description:
Tree Skyness

Crown shyness occurs when the tops of fully grown trees avoid touching each other, forming gaps in the canopy. This piece simulates that phenomena and plays with celestial object avoidance. Features include four seasons, time of day, up to 12 trees, and many special options. HD rendering can be enabled for 8192x8192 resolution. 10% of primary sales will be donated to the fxhash Ukraine fund.

Click to randomize with the same settings.

By Frank Force @KilledByAPixel
Made with Vanilla JavaScript

Controls
1 = Save a 2048x2048 png (or right click save)
2 = Toggle HD (may not work in some environments)
3 = Toggle noise (disable for clearer image)

metadata.name: Dencity #177
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with ‚ù§Ô∏è, code and p5js.

metadata.name: Neural Collapse #233
metadata.description:
What happens when your brain overloads, or when you lose control of your giant robot.

A study on the repetition and stacking of a simple but very dynamic structure.

Everything procedurally generated at runtime.
You can find more informations on the piece, its design and origins, here: https://ulucode.com/wp/neural-collapse/

Interactivity : 
- You can hover your mouse on the connectors to close them... temporarily
- Press and hold the mouse button to slightly move the viewpoint.

- Press "a" to increase quality of the antialiasing (3 levels), at the cost of performances. Especially useful on the palettes using outlines.
- Export a PNG capture at various resolutions by pressing the number keys 1 to 9 (top row or numpad, and only in live mode, after pressing "open"). Resolutions ranges from 720 to 7680 pixels. I recommend starting with "4".

GPU recommended. Best performances on Chrome in general.

I felt it for the first time when I was five years old.

I looked at my mother and knew something bad would happen. 
So I clung to her leg, clutching her dress as if it could save me. 
She tried to pry me off but my grip tightened as she spoke softly in my ear, ‚ÄúDon‚Äôt worry honey don‚Äôt worry nothing will happen to you today.

metadata.name: Takashi's Death #255
metadata.description:
Akira by Katsuhiro Otomo.
A global landmark in the shaping of the Cyberpunk genre, and a watershed title for the medium.

I got my hands on the tank≈çbon(s) more than 20 years ago and those pages upon pages at the end of the third one depicting the destruction of Neo-Tokyo stayed with me ever since. Pages of stunning destruction, leaving me in awe.

This is my generative take on the subject. An attempt to evoke the power of that one panel in a cohesive collection.

Everything procedurally generated at runtime.
You can find more info on the composition here : https://ulucode.com/wp/takashis-death/

Export a PNG capture at various resolutions by pressing the number keys 1 to 9 (top row or numpad, and only in live mode, after pressing "open"). Resolutions ranges from 720 to 7680 pixels ( height ). I recommend starting with "4".

More features are available, but a decent GPU is recommended:
- Press "space" to toggle an animation on/off
- Press "u" to Unlock the camera. You can then :
. Mouse left : Rotate
. Mouse middle/wheel : Zoom
. Mouse right : Translate
. "r" : reset camera
. "a" : change antialiasing quality : 3 settings in rotation. Try this if your framerate is too low.
